The direction vector of the first line is $\begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ -2 \\ -6 \end{pmatrix},$ and the direction vector of the second line is $\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}.$  Then
\begin{align*} \cos \theta &= \frac{\left| \begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ -2 \\ -6 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} \right|}{\left\| \begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ -2 \\ -6 \end{pmatrix} \right\| \left\| \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} \right\|} \\ &= \frac{|(-3)(1) + (-2)(2) + (-6)(2)|}{\sqrt{(-3)^2 + (-2)^2 + (-6)^2} \sqrt{1^2 + 2^2 + 2^2}} \\ &= \frac{|-3 - 4 - 12|}{\sqrt{9 + 4 + 36} \sqrt{1 + 4 + 4}} \\ &= \frac{|-19|}{\sqrt{49} \sqrt{9}} \\ &= \frac{19}{7 \cdot 3} \\ &= \frac{19}{21}. \end{align*}

Final Answer: The final answer is $\boxed{\frac{19}{21}}$

